<p>An Ahrefs study of 6.4 million domains found that 46.1% of WordPress sites receive organic search traffic. Only 1.4% of Wix sites do.</p>
<p>That single stat shapes the entire WordPress vs Wix debate. But the number is misleading without context. WordPress powers 43% of the internet. Most of those sites are actively managed by teams investing in SEO. Most Wix sites are hobby projects or abandoned portfolio pages. The platform did not fail those sites. The site owners never tried.</p>
<p>This guide compares WordPress vs Wix for SEO across 14 factors. No affiliate bias. No recycled opinions from 2019. Just a direct comparison backed by current data and real testing.</p>
<p>We have published 3,500+ blog posts across 70+ industries. We have seen both platforms rank and both platforms stall. The difference is almost never the CMS. It is the strategy behind it.</p>
<p>Here is what you will learn:</p>
<ul>
<li>Which platform gives you more control over <a href="/glossary/technical-seo/">technical SEO</a></li>
<li>How page speed and Core Web Vitals compare with real data</li>
<li>Where Wix has caught up to WordPress (and where it has not)</li>
<li>The true total cost of SEO on each platform</li>
<li>How each platform handles AI search and structured data</li>
<li>Which platform fits your business type and growth trajectory</li>
</ul>
<h2>Quick Verdict</h2>
<p><strong>Best for SEO control and scale:</strong> WordPress</p>
<p><strong>Best for simplicity and built-in SEO:</strong> Wix</p>
<p>WordPress wins for businesses that need advanced SEO, custom schema, full server control, and plugin flexibility. Wix wins for small businesses that want a fast setup with solid default SEO settings and zero maintenance.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>"If you need to rank for competitive keywords in a crowded market, WordPress gives you the tools. If you need a clean site that handles SEO basics automatically, Wix does the job."</p>
</blockquote>
<h2>What Is WordPress?</h2>
<p>WordPress is an open-source content management system that powers 43% of all websites. It holds 63% of the global CMS market share and runs an estimated 605 million sites.</p>
<p>WordPress.org (self-hosted) gives you full control over your site files, server configuration, hosting environment, and every SEO setting. You install it on your own hosting provider. You manage updates, security, and performance.</p>
<p>WordPress.com (hosted) is a simplified version with less control. This comparison focuses on WordPress.org because that is where the SEO advantages live.</p>
<p><strong>WordPress is best for:</strong> Businesses that need granular SEO control, custom development, and the ability to scale content without platform limitations.</p>
<h2>What Is Wix?</h2>
<p>Wix is a hosted website builder with 282 million registered users and over 8 million active sites. It holds 4.3% of the total web and 11% of the CMS market.</p>
<p>Wix earned a bad SEO reputation in its early years due to hashbang URLs and heavy JavaScript rendering. That reputation is outdated. Since 2020, Wix has added clean URLs, structured data, XML sitemaps, robots.txt editing, and full server-side rendering. Google's John Mueller has confirmed on record that Wix sites can rank.</p>
<p>Wix achieved a perfect median Lighthouse SEO score of 100 on desktop and mobile for two consecutive years, according to the Web Almanac. Its usage grew 115% between 2020 and 2025.</p>
<p><strong>Wix is best for:</strong> Small businesses, freelancers, and service providers who want a professional site with solid <a href="/glossary/on-page-seo/">on-page SEO</a> handled automatically.</p>
