<p>WordPress leads in 12 out of 18 categories. Wix matches WordPress in basic on-page SEO elements. The gap widens in <a href="/glossary/technical-seo/">technical SEO</a>, server control, and customization.</p>
<h2>On-Page SEO: WordPress vs Wix</h2>
<p>On-page SEO covers title tags, meta descriptions, headings, keyword placement, and content structure. Both platforms handle these basics well.</p>
<h3>WordPress On-Page SEO</h3>
<p>WordPress requires a plugin for on-page SEO management. The two leading options are Yoast SEO (used on 12+ million sites) and Rank Math (3+ million installs). These plugins add:</p>
<ul>
<li>Real-time content analysis and readability scoring</li>
<li>Title tag and meta description templates</li>
<li>Focus keyword tracking</li>
<li>Internal link suggestions</li>
<li>Social media preview cards</li>
<li>Breadcrumb navigation</li>
</ul>
<p>Rank Math includes a content AI feature that analyzes top-ranking pages and suggests related keywords. Yoast provides a readability score based on sentence length and passive voice usage.</p>
<p>The advantage is depth. WordPress SEO plugins give you more data points per page than any website builder offers natively. If you follow a structured <a href="/blog/on-page-seo-guide/">on-page SEO guide</a>, WordPress gives you every control you need.</p>
<h3>Wix On-Page SEO</h3>
<p>Wix includes on-page SEO settings without any plugin. Every page gets:</p>
<ul>
<li>Editable title tags and meta descriptions</li>
<li>Customizable URL slugs</li>
<li>Heading hierarchy controls (H1 through H6)</li>
<li>Alt text fields for every image</li>
<li>SEO Wiz (step-by-step SEO setup)</li>
<li>SEO patterns for bulk-editing meta templates</li>
</ul>
<p>Wix SEO Wiz walks beginners through basic setup. It connects to Google Search Console, suggests a site title, and checks that meta descriptions exist on key pages.</p>
<p>The limitation is ceiling. Wix covers 80% of what most small businesses need. The other 20% requires features Wix does not offer.</p>
<h3>Verdict: On-Page SEO</h3>
<p><strong>WordPress wins for power users.</strong> The plugin ecosystem provides deeper analysis and more optimization levers. <strong>Wix wins for beginners.</strong> Built-in tools mean zero setup and no plugin conflicts.</p>
<h2>Technical SEO: WordPress vs Wix</h2>
<p><a href="/blog/how-to-do-seo-audit/">Technical SEO</a> determines whether search engines can crawl, index, and understand your site. This is where the platforms diverge most.</p>
<h3>WordPress Technical SEO</h3>
<p>WordPress gives you direct access to:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>robots.txt</strong>. Edit the file directly on your server. Add or remove crawl directives, block specific directories, and reference your sitemap. Read our full <a href="/blog/optimize-robots-txt/">robots.txt optimization guide</a>.</li>
<li><strong>.htaccess</strong>. Control redirects, URL rewriting, security headers, and caching rules at the server level.</li>
<li><strong>Custom schema markup</strong>. Add any <a href="/blog/schema-markup-for-blog-posts/">schema type</a> via plugins or custom code. Product, FAQ, HowTo, LocalBusiness, Article, and more.</li>
<li><strong>XML sitemaps</strong>. Generate with Yoast, Rank Math, or a dedicated plugin. Customize which content types appear. Split sitemaps by category. Learn how to <a href="/blog/create-xml-sitemap/">create and submit an XML sitemap</a>.</li>
<li><strong>Server-side caching</strong>. Choose from WP Rocket, W3 Total Cache, or server-level solutions like Varnish and Redis.</li>
<li><strong>Database optimization</strong>. Clean post revisions, transients, and orphaned metadata.</li>
<li><strong>CDN configuration</strong>. Use Cloudflare, Bunny CDN, or any provider you prefer.</li>
</ul>
<p>The downside is maintenance. Plugin conflicts cause crawl errors. Misconfigured caching breaks rendering. A bad theme can generate duplicate content. WordPress requires ongoing technical attention.</p>
<h3>Wix Technical SEO</h3>
<p>Wix handles most technical SEO automatically:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>XML sitemaps</strong>. Generated and submitted automatically</li>
<li><strong>SSL</strong>. Enabled by default on all sites</li>
<li><strong>Server-side rendering</strong>. Pages render on the server, not in the browser</li>
<li><strong>Structured data</strong>. BlogPosting schema added automatically to blog posts</li>
<li><strong>Robots.txt</strong>. Editable through the dashboard</li>
<li><strong>Canonical URLs</strong>. Set automatically to prevent duplicate content</li>
</ul>
<p>The trade-off is control. You cannot access server files. You cannot install custom caching layers. You cannot edit the underlying HTML structure. Advanced <a href="/glossary/technical-seo/">technical SEO</a> work like log file analysis, crawl budget optimization, or custom header configurations is not possible.</p>
<h3>Verdict: Technical SEO</h3>
<p><strong>WordPress wins by a wide margin.</strong> If your SEO strategy requires custom schema, server-level optimization, or advanced crawl management, WordPress is the only option.</p>
<h2>Page Speed and Core Web Vitals</h2>
<p>Page speed directly affects rankings. Google uses <a href="/glossary/core-web-vitals/">Core Web Vitals</a> as a ranking signal.</p>
<h3>WordPress Speed</h3>
<p>A well-optimized WordPress site loads in under 2 seconds. The key word is "well-optimized."</p>
<p>Speed depends entirely on your hosting provider, theme, number of plugins, image optimization, and caching setup. A WordPress site on cheap shared hosting with 40 plugins and uncompressed images will be slower than Wix.</p>
<p>A WordPress site on managed hosting (WP Engine, Kinsta, Cloudways) with a lightweight theme (GeneratePress, Kadence), WP Rocket caching, and WebP images will outperform nearly any website builder.</p>
<p>WordPress gives you full control over every Core Web Vital:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>LCP (Largest Contentful Paint)</strong>. Optimize hero images, preload critical assets, use a CDN</li>
<li><strong>INP (Interaction to Next Paint)</strong>. Minimize JavaScript, defer non-critical scripts</li>
<li><strong>CLS (Cumulative Layout Shift)</strong>. Set explicit image dimensions, inline critical CSS</li>
</ul>
<p>For a detailed breakdown, read our guide on <a href="/blog/improve-core-web-vitals/">improving Core Web Vitals</a>.</p>
<h3>Wix Speed</h3>
<p>Here is the data point that surprises most people: Wix sites pass Core Web Vitals at a higher rate than WordPress sites.</p>
<p>According to CrUX data from the Chrome User Experience Report, 70-75% of Wix origins pass all three Core Web Vitals thresholds. Only 33-44% of WordPress origins do.</p>
<p>This does not mean Wix is faster. It means the average Wix site is faster than the average WordPress site. WordPress has a higher ceiling but a much lower floor. Bad hosting, unoptimized themes, and plugin bloat drag the average down.</p>
<p>Wix infrastructure includes a global CDN, automatic image compression (WebP and AVIF), and server-side rendering. You cannot control JavaScript bundling, third-party script loading, or server configuration. But you also cannot break it.</p>
<p>The improvement trajectory matters. Wix sites in 2026 are measurably faster than Wix sites in 2022. They still cannot match a purpose-built WordPress stack on Kinsta or WP Engine with a lightweight theme.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" alt="Core Web Vitals pass rate comparison showing Wix at 70-75% vs WordPress at 33-44%" src="/images/blog/wordpress-vs-wix-cwv-comparison.webp" /></p>
<h3>Verdict: Page Speed</h3>
<p><strong>WordPress wins. With a caveat.</strong> An optimized WordPress site is faster. But most WordPress sites are not optimized. If you will not invest in proper hosting and performance tuning, Wix delivers more consistent speed out of the box.</p>
<h2>Content Publishing and Blogging</h2>
<p>Content drives organic traffic. Your platform's blogging system directly affects how efficiently you publish SEO-optimized articles.</p>
<h3>WordPress for Blogging</h3>
<p>WordPress was built as a blogging platform. It excels at content:</p>
<ul>
<li>Native categories and tags for content organization</li>
<li>Custom post types for different content formats</li>
<li>Gutenberg block editor with reusable blocks</li>
<li>Revision history for every post</li>
<li>Scheduled publishing</li>
<li>RSS feeds for content syndication</li>
<li>60,000+ plugins for extending functionality</li>
</ul>
<p>WordPress handles <a href="/blog/internal-linking-blog-posts/">internal linking</a> through plugins like Link Whisper or Rank Math. You can build <a href="/blog/what-is-topical-authority/">topical authority</a> through content clusters with full control over URL structure and taxonomy.</p>
<p>For businesses publishing 10+ articles per month, WordPress provides the infrastructure to scale. Content teams can use editorial workflows, user roles, and staging environments.</p>
<h3>Wix for Blogging</h3>
<p>Wix has a capable blog module with:</p>
<ul>
<li>Rich text editor with media embedding</li>
<li>Categories and tags</li>
<li>Scheduled publishing</li>
<li>SEO fields per post (title, description, slug)</li>
<li>Automatic BlogPosting schema</li>
<li>Built-in social sharing</li>
</ul>
<p>The blog editor is simpler than WordPress Gutenberg. For basic blog publishing, this is an advantage. Less complexity means fewer formatting errors.</p>
<p>The limitation shows at scale. Wix does not support custom post types. Content taxonomy options are basic. Managing 200+ blog posts on Wix becomes cumbersome compared to WordPress.</p>
<h3>Verdict: Content Publishing</h3>
<p><strong>WordPress wins for scale.</strong> If your SEO strategy depends on publishing volume, WordPress handles it better. <strong>Wix wins for simplicity.</strong> If you publish 2-4 posts per month, Wix covers the basics without overhead.</p>
