<h2>E-Commerce SEO</h2>
<p>If you sell products online, <a href="/blog/ecommerce-seo-guide/">e-commerce SEO</a> adds another layer of comparison.</p>
<h3>WordPress + WooCommerce</h3>
<p>WooCommerce is the most popular e-commerce plugin for WordPress. It powers over 5 million online stores. For SEO, it provides:</p>
<ul>
<li>Custom product URLs</li>
<li>Product schema markup (price, availability, reviews)</li>
<li>Category and tag pages for keyword targeting</li>
<li>Breadcrumb navigation</li>
<li>Faceted filtering (with proper canonical handling via plugins)</li>
<li>Integration with Yoast WooCommerce SEO or Rank Math</li>
</ul>
<p>WooCommerce gives you full control over product page structure. You can add comparison tables, size guides, FAQ sections, and custom fields that help pages rank for long-tail keywords.</p>
<h3>Wix E-Commerce</h3>
<p>Wix Stores includes:</p>
<ul>
<li>Product pages with SEO fields</li>
<li>Category pages</li>
<li>Basic product schema (auto-generated)</li>
<li>Mobile-optimized checkout</li>
</ul>
<p>Wix e-commerce is functional for small catalogs (under 500 products). The SEO tools are adequate for basic product optimization. But you lack the depth of WooCommerce for advanced product SEO like custom faceted navigation, programmatic product pages, or complex internal linking between products and blog content.</p>
<h3>Verdict: E-Commerce SEO</h3>
<p><strong>WordPress + WooCommerce wins.</strong> The customization depth and plugin ecosystem give you more ranking opportunities per product page.</p>
<h2>Local SEO Features</h2>
<p>For service businesses, <a href="/blog/local-seo-guide/">local SEO</a> determines whether you appear in Google Maps and the local pack.</p>
<h3>WordPress Local SEO</h3>
<p>WordPress handles local SEO through plugins:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Rank Math</strong>. LocalBusiness schema, multiple locations, opening hours</li>
<li><strong>Yoast Local SEO</strong>. Premium add-on for multi-location businesses</li>
<li><strong>Schema Pro</strong>. Advanced local schema generation</li>
<li>Google Maps embedding via shortcodes or blocks</li>
</ul>
<p>You can build location-specific landing pages with unique content, custom URLs, and targeted internal links. WordPress gives you full control over your local SEO architecture.</p>
<h3>Wix Local SEO</h3>
<p>Wix includes:</p>
<ul>
<li>Business info fields (address, phone, hours) in site settings</li>
<li>Automatic LocalBusiness schema when business info is filled</li>
<li>Google Maps integration</li>
<li>Built-in contact forms</li>
</ul>
<p>Wix handles the basics of local SEO well. For a single-location business, Wix provides everything you need without plugins.</p>
<p>Multi-location businesses will find Wix limiting. Building 20+ location pages with unique content and schema requires manual work that WordPress plugins automate.</p>
<h3>Verdict: Local SEO</h3>
<p><strong>Tie for single locations.</strong> Both platforms handle single-location local SEO. <strong>WordPress wins for multi-location businesses</strong> that need scalable local landing pages.</p>
