<h2>FAQ</h2>
<p><strong>Is WordPress better than Wix for SEO?</strong></p>
<p>WordPress offers more SEO control, a deeper plugin ecosystem, and full server access. For competitive keywords and large-scale content strategies, WordPress is the better choice. Wix handles SEO fundamentals well and is a strong option for small businesses in low-competition markets.</p>
<p><strong>Can Wix sites rank on Google?</strong></p>
<p>Yes. Google's John Mueller has confirmed that Wix sites can rank. Wix earned a perfect Lighthouse SEO score of 100 for two consecutive years. The platform handles crawling, indexing, and basic on-page SEO well. Ranking depends on your content quality and backlink profile, not just your CMS.</p>
<p><strong>Does Wix have SEO plugins like WordPress?</strong></p>
<p>Wix does not have an equivalent plugin ecosystem. Instead, Wix builds SEO features directly into the platform. You get title tags, meta descriptions, schema markup, sitemaps, and redirects without installing anything. For advanced needs like custom schema types or automated internal linking, WordPress plugins offer more options.</p>
<p><strong>Is WordPress SEO free?</strong></p>
<p>The core WordPress software is free. The essential SEO plugins (Yoast SEO and Rank Math) have free versions that cover most needs. You pay for hosting ($5-$50 per month), a domain ($10-$15 per year), and optional premium plugins. Total annual cost ranges from $150 to $600 depending on your setup.</p>
<p><strong>Should I migrate from Wix to WordPress for SEO?</strong></p>
<p>Migrate only if you have hit Wix's ceiling. Signs include: you need custom schema types Wix does not support, your site loads too slowly and you cannot fix it, you publish 10+ articles per month and need editorial workflows, or you need server-level optimizations for Core Web Vitals. If Wix handles your current SEO needs, stay. Migration carries risk (broken URLs, lost rankings) and costs time.</p>
<p><strong>Which platform is better for local SEO?</strong></p>
<p>Both platforms handle single-location local SEO well. WordPress has an edge for multi-location businesses because plugins like Rank Math and Schema Pro automate LocalBusiness schema across many pages. Wix is sufficient for a single storefront or office. Read our full <a href="/blog/local-seo-guide/">local SEO guide</a> for platform-agnostic optimization tips.</p>
<h2>The Bottom Line</h2>
<p>WordPress gives you a higher SEO ceiling. Wix gives you a higher SEO floor.</p>
<p>If you have the technical resources and plan to invest in content, WordPress will outperform Wix in competitive markets. If you need a clean, professional site with solid SEO defaults and zero maintenance, Wix delivers without the overhead.</p>
<p>The platform matters less than what you publish on it. A Wix site with 50 well-optimized blog posts will outrank a WordPress site with 5 thin pages every time. Consistent, high-quality content is the factor that separates sites that rank from sites that do not.</p>
<p>Choose the platform that fits your resources. Then focus on publishing content that earns rankings.</p>
